sec.p:
In the method of Barrs and Weatherley [30], fresh leaves were weighed immediately after sampling (FW), leaves were placed in distilled water for 24 h and reweighed (TW), after which the leaves were dried in an oven at 70 °C for 24 h and reweighed (DW). The relative water content (RWC) was determined using the following formula.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\text{R}\text{W}\text{C}\:\left(\text{\%}\right)=\left(\frac{\text{F}\text{W}-\text{D}\text{W}}{\text{T}\text{W}-\text{D}\text{W}}\right)\times\:\:100$$\end{document}

To measure the amount of electrolyte leakage from leaves, leaf pieces were incubated in distilled water for 24 h on a shaker at 25 °C [31]. Then, the electrical conductivity of the samples was measured using an EC meter (EC1). After the samples were autoclaved for 20 min at 121 °C, their electrical conductivity was measured again (EC2). The following formula was used to calculate the electrolyte leakage rate.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\text{E}\text{L}\:\left(\text{\%}\right)=\left(\frac{\text{E}\text{C}1}{\text{E}\text{C}2}\right)\times\:100$$\end{document}

